
[1]sentiment

   SEN'TIMENT, n. [from L. sentio, to feel, perceive or think.]

   1. Properly. a thought prompted by passion or feeling.

   2. In a popular sense, Thought; opinion; notion; judgement; the
   decilion of the mind formed by deliberation or reasoning. Thus in
   deliberative bodies, every man has the privilege of delivering his
   sentiments upon questions, motions and bills.

   3. The sense, thought or opinion contained in words, but considered as
   distinct from them. We may like the sentiment, when we dislike the
   language.

   4. Sensibility; feeling.
